occurrences.line_text: Sith late he fled from his too earnest foe:
He turned backe, and would haue fled arere;
With such amazement, that in haste he fled,
High ouer hilles and ouer dales he fled,
Still fled he forward, looking backward still,
Far off aspyde a young man, the which fled
His former suit, and from them fled apace;
Long so she fled, and so he follow'd long;
But fled away with ghastly dreriment,
Was fled to hell, surcharg'd with spoile and theft.
But turnd her face, and fled away for euermore.
The which another did, who now is fled with shame.
The whiles his guilefull groome was fled away:
From which he lately had through reskew fled:
They all were fled for feare, but whether, nether kond.
Fled fast into the towne, and her sole victor left.
Yet fled she fast, and both them farre outwent,
Durst not endure their sight, but fled from place to place.
Where so he fled, he followd him apace:
Whom when his other fellowes saw, they fled
Whose grudging ghost was thereout fled and past,
And entraunce wonne. Streight th'other fled away,
Durst not abide, but fled away for feare,
Yet when she fled into that couert greaue,
He quite forsooke, and fled himselfe away for feare.
In following of him, that fled so fast,
Yet ere he fled, he with his tooth impure
They fled, and fast into the wood did get:
That few of them he left aliue, which fled,
He fled from roome to roome, from place to place,
And fled away with all the speede she mought,
With those two Carles, fled fast away, afeard
Long thus she fled, till that at last she thought
From thence into the open fields he fled,
But why when I them saw, fled they away from me?
Through cowherd feare he fled away as fast,
Had from their maisters fled, & now sought hyre elswhere.
Fled from his wrath, and did themselues conuay
Great whirlpooles, which all fishes make to flee,
Of scorched deaw, do not in th'aire more lightly flee.
Yet did the smart remaine, though he himselfe did flee.
At sight thereof, and from her presence flee:
His goodly conquest of the golden fleece,
All mindlesse of the Golden fleece, which made them striue.
Fight for the rule of the rich fleeced flocke,
Keeping their fleecie flockes, as they were hyred,
Her fleecie flocke; but Coridon most helpe did giue.
His fleecie flocke vpon the playnes around,
Their fleecy flowres they tenderly did steepe,
For that same golden fleecy Ram, which bore
And in frayle wood on Adrian gulfe doth fleet,
That one of those same Islands, which doe fleet
May her perhaps containe, that else would algates fleet.
And then another, till that likewise fleet;
How soone would yee assemble many a fleete,
Full of great lumpes of flesh and gobbets raw,
With the fraile flesh; at last it flitted is,
And beat their brests, and naked flesh to teare.
And a dry dropsie through his flesh did flow:
In tender flesh, that streames of bloud down flow,
My fearefull flesh did tremble at their strife,
No faith so fast (quoth she) but flesh does paire.
Flesh may empaire (quoth he) but reason can repaire.
Decayd, and all his flesh shronk vp like withered flowres.
That makes fraile flesh to feare the bitter waue?
Die shall all flesh? what then must needs be donne,
And euer as superfluous flesh did rot
And rend his flesh, and his owne synewes eat.
And pyn'd his flesh, to keepe his body low and chast.
The steely head stucke fast still in his flesh,
For he was flesh: (all flesh doth frailtie breed.)
For he was flesh: (all flesh doth frailtie breed.)
In her sonnes flesh, to minde reuengement,
Her face so faire as flesh it seemed not,
Deepe in his flesh, and opened wide a red floodgate.
Deepe in their flesh, quite through the yron walles,
In his owne flesh, and make way to the liuing spright.
But I, that am fraile flesh and earthly wight,
His Lords owne flesh. Therewith out of his hond
He swaruing with the force, within his flesh
Of the fraile flesh, relenting to their rage,
Flesh without bloud, a person without spright,
But lou'd their natiue flesh against all kind,
But had no powre in his soft flesh to bite:
The flesh therewith she suppled and did steepe,
And did in stocke of earthly flesh enrace,
That in her pregnant flesh they shortly fructifide.
His rugged flesh, and rent his ragged heare:
That feeds on womens flesh, as others feede on gras.
Full many wounds in his corrupted flesh
Her natiue flesh, and staine her brothers bowre,
The sight whereof in his congealed flesh,
That fed on liuing flesh, & druncke mens vitall blood.
And in their flesh a griesly passage rend,
But some celestiall shape, that flesh did beare:
Could stay, but to the tender flesh it went,
Of earthly mould, and form'd of flesh and bone,
To teare his flesh in peeces for his sin.
And proud rebellious flesh to mortify.
With flesh of men, whom through fell tyranny
Of Bacchus Priests her owne deare flesh did teare.
The flesh of men, to Gods owne likenesse framed,
Those he deuoures, they say, both flesh and bone:
That many wounds into his flesh it made,
Her flesh for felnesse, which she inward hid:
All flesh is frayle, and full of ficklenesse,
Ne fed on flesh, ne euer of wyld beast
Made in his tender flesh, but whole them all he found.
That none of them in his soft flesh did bite,
To eate the flesh of men, whom they mote fynde,
But of her dainty flesh they did deuize
And his owne flesh he readie was to teare:
Do seize vpon some beast, whose flesh is bare,
And made wide furrowes in their fleshes fraile,
But when strong passion, or weake fleshlinesse
And thousand other wayes, to bait his fleshly hookes.
Ne fleshly brest can armed be so sound,
And who most trustes in arme of fleshly might,
Come, come away, fraile, seely, fleshly wight,
What man is he, that boasts of fleshly might,
Else neuer could the force of fleshly arme,
And feeble nature cloth'd with fleshly tyre,
What time th'eternall Lord in fleshly slime
For she was giuen all to fleshly lust,
But as a coale to kindle fleshly flame,
Now ranckleth in this same fraile fleshly mould,
So feeble is the powre of fleshly arme.
Out of her fleshly ferme fled to the place of paine.
That is ingenerate in fleshly slime.
That he with fleshly weedes would them attire:
Fleshly corruption, nor mortall paine.
In fleshly lust were mingled both yfere,
Did wallow in all other fleshly myre,
His wearie ghost assoyld from fleshly band,
With fleshly weaknesse, which no creature may
Of men and beasts; and fed on fleshly gore,
Therefore they mote not taste of fleshly food,
Then farewell fleshly force; I see thy pride is nought.
Who therewith flesht, vpon him set anew,
But with that percing noise flew open quite, or brast.
And euery dore of freewill open flew.
And at him fiercely flew, with courage fild,
Did loose his vele by chaunce, and open flew:
Als flew his steed, as he his bands had brast,
And therewithall he fiercely at him flew,
And after him Owles and Night-rauens flew,
About them flew, and fild their sayles with feare:
And flew about his heeles in wanton wize,
And her faire yellow locks behind her flew,
Wherewith enrag'd she fiercely at them flew,
That through his haberieon the forkehead flew,
Fiercely he flew vpon that wicked feend,
With which that yron wicket open flew,
That brasen dore flew open, and in went
Like two mad mastiffes each on other flew,
Which straight flew ope, and gaue her way to ride.
And flew away, as lightly as the wind:
But that sweet bird departing, flew forth right
Eftsoones she flew vnto his fearelesse hand,
But none of them (so fast away he flew)
Flew first abroad, and all mens eares possest,
And all about her necke and shoulders flew
They each at other tyrannously flew;
But streight the winged words out of his ballaunce flew.
But here and there before his presence flew,
And through the thickest like a Lyon flew,
Like a fell Lionesse at him she flew,
With her sharpe Cemitare at him she flew,
From which like mazed deare, dismayfully they flew.
Vp to the rocke he ran, and thereon flew
With that so furiously at him he flew,
She flew at him, like to an hellish feend,
Vppon her wide great wings, and strongly flew
With that he fiercely at him flew, and layd
But at him flew, and with his speare him smot;
And with mad mood againe vpon him flew,
Like a fell Lion at him fiercely flew,
With his sharpe sword he fiercely at him flew,
He flew vpon him, like a greedy kight
But seeing Calidore, away he flew,
Like sparkes of fire, which fall in sclender flex,
And oft would flie away. O who can tell
Still seeking him, that from her still did flie,
From whom her booteth not at all to flie;
To flie the vengeance for his outrage dew;
They both nigh were, and each bad other flie:
Dismay with feare, or cause one foot to flie,
That she note stirre. Then gan her sonne to flie
Or winged canuas with the wind to flie,
Vile Miscreant (said he) whither doest thou flie
Did flie abacke, and made him vainely swinke:
And farre before a light-foot Page did flie,
Whence as he to those woodie hils did flie,
No need to bid her fast away to flie;
As it befell, that she could flie no more,
With heapes of strokes, which he at him let flie,
So did one soule out of his bodie flie
Are wont, before they may to heauen flie,
And missing it, faine from themselues to flie;
And her pursu'd as fast as she did flie:
That forst him flie abacke, himselfe to saue:
Whom seeing flie, she speedily poursewed
A Squire came gallopping, as he would flie;
That all at once at him gan fiercely flie,
The raging seas, and makst the stormes to flie;
And with his iron flale at it let flie,
Each one did flie; their hearts began to faile,
But vaine it was to thinke from him to flie.
Through all the fields and vallies did before him flie.
With his rude yron flaile, they gan to flie,
Who still from him as fast away did flie,
From whom she earst so fast away did flie;
Whom Calidore perceiuing fast to flie,
Bad him to flie with all the speed he could,
With which he layd about, and made them fast to flie.
In winters wrathfull time, he forced him to flie.
Snatcheth his sword, and fiercely to him flies;
No foote to foe. The flashing fier flies
Sir Treuisan flies from Despayre,
And marueiles at himselfe, still as he flies:
Whiles in the aire their clustring army flies,
But fame now flies, that of a forreine foe
Full fast she flies, and farre afore him goes,
Like foolish flies about an hony crocke,
With dreadfull force he flies at her byliue,
And round about her flocke, like many flies,
Like as the wounded Whale to shore flies fro[m] the maine.
At which Cocytus quakes, and Styx is put to flight.
A Dragon fiers encountreth in his flight,
He by a priuie Posterne tooke his flight,
And the Robuckes in flight to ouertake,
He forst to castle strong to take their flight,
And eke from whom make ye this hasty flight:
And with strong flight did forcibly diuide
To trusse the pray too heauie for his flight;
Who him r'encountring fierce, as hauke in flight,
From off the earth to take his aerie flight.
And grieued at her flight; yet durst he not
Feare gaue her wings, and rage enforst my flight;
(Said he) but whither with such hasty flight
After that varlets flight, it was not long,
Gaz'd after him, as fowle escapt by flight;
That may not hope by flight to scape aliue,
knightes to flight compell.
And chaste so fiercely after fearfull flight,
The reach of men, through flight into fond mischief fell.
Yet such, as were through former flight preseru'd,
And in his flight the villein turn'd his face,
Suddeinly an innumerable flight
And meet respect of honour put to flight:
Tho whenas all were put to shamefull flight,
Of dreadfull things the same was put to flight,
Least afterwards it be too late to take thy flight.
But nothing might relent her hastie flight;
Their brother to reproch and shamefull flight:
At last in vaine was forst to turne his flight,
From her in flight, he found, that did him sore apall.
And gan encrease his speed, as she encreast her flight.
But when he stayd, to flight againe she did her take.
Their purpost flight, free from all mens reclame;
Ne stayd his flight, nor fearefull agony,
And like a winged horse he tooke his flight,
He falleth nigh to ground, and scarse recouereth flight.
And makes her feare a spur to hast her flight:
Yet saw her forward still to make her flight,
To seeke by flight her fellowship t'eschew,
For he was swift as swallow in her flight,
But from the water to the land betooke his flight.
As when a Faulcon hath with nimble flight
Whose other wing, now made vnmeete for flight,
She had not rid the mountenance of a flight,
Vnder Alcides club, streight tooke his flight
Had hid themselues, or taken further flight:
Whereto she euer list to make her hardy flight.
Gainst which no flight nor rescue mote auayle,
His heart gan faint, and streight he tooke his flight
But I the measure of her flight doe search,
And to betake him selfe to fearefull flight;
But follow'd fast the Monster in his flight:
He had him ouertaken in his flight.
From bels and iesses, which did let her flight,
Thinking by speed to ouertake his flight;
As when a cast of Faulcons make their flight
To let them downe before his flightes end:
Or flings aloft, or treads downe in the flore,
And all their glory to the ground downe flings,
And said, Faire Lady hart of flint would rew
That hart of flint a sunder could haue rift:
Headed with flint, and feathers bloudie dide,
For on a sandie hill, that still did flit,
And in his hand two darts exceeding flit,
For the flit barke, obaying to her mind,
In PhÃ¦drias flit barke ouer that perlous shard.
The life did flit away out of her nest,
Such as in idle fantasies doe flit:
His falsed faith, and loue too lightly flit,
Therewith a while she her flit fancy fed,
Was from her fled, as flit as ayerie Doue,
And her flit Palfrey did so well apply
That on the rockes he fell so flit and light,
Fearing least from her cage the wearie soule would flit.
Now like a Stag, now like a faulcon flit:
I with that Squire agreede away to flit,
Would flit a litle forward, and then stay,
Ne yeelded foote, ne once abacke did flit,
Thence doth by Huntingdon and Cambridge flit;
With the fraile flesh; at last it flitted is,
So hardly he the flitted life does win,
On whom he got faire Pegasus, that flitteth in the ayre.
Her flitting partes, and element vnsound,
Do rather choose my flitting houres to spend,
The flitting skyes, like flying Pursuiuant,
Was alwaies flitting as the wauering wind,
High on an hill, his flocke to vewen wide,
Fight for the rule of the rich fleeced flocke,
A seely Lambe farre from the flocke does take,
Flocke all about to see her louely face:
Amidst a flocke of Damzels fresh and gay,
Doe flocke, awaiting shortly to obtaine
Do flocke about, my deare my daughter is;
And round about him flocke impetuously,
A flocke of litle loues, and sports, and ioyes,
Therefore the vulgar did about him flocke,
And round about her flocke, like many flies,
Fly like a flocke of doues before a Faulcons vew.
And streight vnto her litle flocke did fare:
Her fleecie flocke; but Coridon most helpe did giue.
After her flocke she in their fold had tyde,
The fields my food, my flocke my rayment breed;
Which to thee flocke, to heare thy louely layes;
His fleecie flocke vpon the playnes around,
They flocked all about her bleeding wound,
Thus flocked all the folke him round about,
And fatall birds about them flocked were,
And with his sword disperst the raskall flockes,
Keeping their fleecie flockes, as they were hyred,
A rauenous Wolfe amongst the scattered flockes.
And shepheards singing to their flockes, that fed,
Their happie flockes, nor daunger to them draw:
And my flockes father daily doth amend it.
The whiles their flockes in shadowes shrouded bee,
Some flockes of sheepe and shepheards to espy;
To hyre them well, if they their flockes would keepe:
To keepe their flockes for litle hyre and chepe:
And also all those flockes, which they before
Flocking together in confusde array,
Who flocking round about them, as a swarme
And all the Brigants flocking in great store,
Their tender flocks, now being fully fed,
And droue away their flocks, with other much disorder.
And feed an hundred flocks, there now not one he found.
The selfe same flocks, the which those theeues had reft
Of feends infernall flockt on euery side,
About their Lady first they flockt arownd,
Of persons flockt, whose names is hard to read:
Her warlike maides about her flockt so fast,
About him flockt, and hard at him did lay;
And dead mens bones, which round about were flong,
He flong it from him, and deuoyd of dreed,
She flong, and her faire deawy lockes yrent,
Which to his mother told, despeire she from her flong.
And friskt, and flong aloft, and louted low on knee.
And come to fiery flood of Phlegeton,
And made an open passage for the gushing flood.
And meetes a flood, that doth his passage stay,
Vpon the banke, yet wilt thy selfe not passe the flood?
From which fast trickled forth a siluer flood,
Some wrestle, some do run, some bathe in christall flood.
The bankes are ouerflowen, when stopped is the flood.
Griefe is a flood, and loue a monster fell;
The flood of drops, the Monster filth did breede:
But bent his hastie course towards the idle flood.
The varlet saw, when to the flood he came,
Fro me do flow into an ample flood,
In a blacke flood which flow'd about it round;
Wyde was the wound, and a large lukewarme flood,
Like Noyes great flood, with their importune sway,
Like a great water flood, that tombling low
So pure and shiny, that the siluer flood
Then th'one her selfe low ducked in the flood,
Right as he entring was into the flood,
As he that striues to stop a suddein flood,
The riuall slaine, the victour through the flood
As she sate carelesse by a cristall flood,
That with the wasting of his vitall flood,
Thinking to hide the depth by troubling of the flood.
More great then th'eares of Elephants by Indus flood.
The place there ouerflowne, seemd like a sodaine flood.
And breaking forth, dare tempt the deepest flood,
Pactolus glistring with his golden flood,
Encloseth Corke with his deuided flood;
In vaine loud crying, and into the flood
Which from their riuen sides forth gushed like a flood.
Deepe in his flesh, and opened wide a red floodgate.
Large floods of bloud adowne their sides did raile;
But floods of bloud could not them satisfie:
The fields, the floods, the heauens with one consent
On euery side floting the floods emong:
Helpe me to tell the names of all those floods,
And Sture, that parteth with his pleasant floods
The which in floods and fountaines doe appere,
But all the floore (too filthy to be told)
And all the floore was vnderneath their feet
Both roofe, and floore, and wals were all of gold,
Whilst freshest Flora her with Yuie girlond crownd.
That seemd as fresh as Flora in her prime,
And filles with flowres faire Floraes painted lap:
With all the ornaments of Floraes pride,
Where entred in, his foot could find no flore,
Or flings aloft, or treads downe in the flore,
And many Giants left on groning flore;
Or his dead corse should fall vpon the flore;
But his dead corse vpon the flore fell nathemore.
Where sitting on the flore the Hag she found,
And forth issewd, as on the ready flore
Or that the flore to shrinke he did auyse,
To rest he layd him downe vpon the flore,
And spredding ouer all the flore alone,
With that he threw her rudely on the flore,
That all the peece he shaked from the flore,
So long they fought, that all the grassie flore
Did enter in, and slew the Porter on the flore.
There he that knight found lying on the flore,
That with their bloud did all the flore imbrew,
It was the same, which lately Florimel had lost.
Then forth he brought his snowy Florimele,
faire Florimell is chaced:
Faire Florimell of Arthur is
Prince Arthur heares of Florimell:
And is ycleped Florimell the faire,
Faire Florimell belou'd of many a knight,
But he sets nought at all by Florimell:
And foure, since Florimell the Court for-went,
Affrighted had the fairest Florimell,
That was to weet, the goodly Florimell;
The witches sonne loues Florimell:
So fled faire Florimell from her vaine feare,
As Florimell fled from that Monster yond,
Whereon faire Florimell was wont to ride,
Which he supposed donne to Florimell,
To tell what tydings of faire Florimell became.
Like to Florimell,
Another Florimell, in shape and looke
Himselfe to fashion likest Florimell,
Which Florimell had left behind her late,
Well weened he, that fairest Florimell
But Florimell her selfe was farre away,
Was Florimell, when Proteus she did see thereby.
But Florimell with him vnto his bowre he bore.
Thither he brought the sory Florimell,
And suddein parture of faire Florimell,
Henceforth for euer Florimell to be.
Blandamour winnes false Florimell,
The snowy Florimell, whose beautie bright
For sure the fayrest Florimell him seemed,
Till seeing her, that Florimell did seme,
They said, it was for loue of Florimell.
That fayrest Florimell was present there in place.
For none aliue but ioy'd in Florimell,
That dare fro me thinke Florimell to take.
Well knowne to appertaine to Florimell,
That chaleng'd ought in Florimell, saue they alone.
For loue of Florimell:
For that rich girdle of faire Florimell,
It was to weete that snowy Florimell,
So Florimell with Ate forth was brought,
And Florimell him fowly gan reuile,
of famous Florimell:
Shall fall the girdle of faire Florimell:
There Florimell in her first ages flowre
And very Florimell, did her display:
Yet all were glad there Florimell to see;
Yet thought that Florimell was not so faire as shee.
That Florimell her selfe in all mens vew
But Florimell exceedingly did fret,
Since with the rest she went not after Florimell.
So whylome didst thou to faire Florimell;
Those foure were they, from whom false Florimell
To let faire Florimell in bands remayne,
Marin for loue of Florimell,
That Florimell it was, which wrought his paine,
But vnto her deliuered Florimell.
Artegall heares of Florimell,
But chiefely of the fairest Florimell,
The spousals of faire Florimell,
So comes it now to Florimell by tourne,
To chalenge all in right of Florimell,
Fayre Florimell, into the common hall,
And then to him came fayrest Florimell,
And said, that surely Florimell it was,
Or if it were not Florimell so tride,
That Florimell her selfe she then did pas.
The more to be true Florimell he did surmize.
Which didst that seruice vnto Florimell.
Is not (I wager) Florimell at all;
For proofe whereof, he bad them Florimell forth call.
Presented to the fayrest Florimell;
Till Florimell about her fastned it.
Whilest thus they busied were bout Florimell,
Bold Marinell with Florimell the fayre,
